webpackJsonp([0xbb0b1d49b4a1],{411:function(e,a){e.exports={data:{markdownRemark:{html:'<p>Elements, attributes, and attribute values are semantic according to the\nHTML5 Specification.</p>\n<p>These definitions allow HTML processors, such as Web browsers, screen readers\nor search engines, to present and use documents and applications in a wide\nvariety of contexts that the author might not have considered.</p>\n<p>This enables a single document to be used by:</p>\n<ul>\n<li>Different types of browsers (desktop vs mobile),</li>\n<li>Screen readers for the visually impaired,</li>\n<li>Indexing by search engines,</li>\n<li>Navigation by making use of document outlines, and</li>\n<li>Table of content generators.</li>\n</ul>\n<p><strong>Note</strong>: This post will not go in depth but will simply highlight some of the design\nchanges from HTML4.</p>\n<h2 id="simplified"><a href="#simplified" aria-hidden="true" class="anchor"><svg aria-hidden="true" height="16" version="1.1" viewBox="0 0 16 16" width="16"><path fill-rule="evenodd" d="M4 9h1v1H4c-1.5 0-3-1.69-3-3.5S2.55 3 4 3h4c1.45 0 3 1.69 3 3.5 0 1.41-.91 2.72-2 3.25V8.59c.58-.45 1-1.27 1-2.09C10 5.22 8.98 4 8 4H4c-.98 0-2 1.22-2 2.5S3 9 4 9zm9-3h-1v1h1c1 0 2 1.22 2 2.5S13.98 12 13 12H9c-.98 0-2-1.22-2-2.5 0-.83.42-1.64 1-2.09V6.25c-1.09.53-2 1.84-2 3.25C6 11.31 7.55 13 9 13h4c1.45 0 3-1.69 3-3.5S14.5 6 13 6z"></path></svg></a>Simplified</h2>\n<h3 id="doctype"><a href="#doctype" aria-hidden="true" class="anchor"><svg aria-hidden="true" height="16" version="1.1" viewBox="0 0 16 16" width="16"><path fill-rule="evenodd" d="M4 9h1v1H4c-1.5 0-3-1.69-3-3.5S2.55 3 4 3h4c1.45 0 3 1.69 3 3.5 0 1.41-.91 2.72-2 3.25V8.59c.58-.45 1-1.27 1-2.09C10 5.22 8.98 4 8 4H4c-.98 0-2 1.22-2 2.5S3 9 4 9zm9-3h-1v1h1c1 0 2 1.22 2 2.5S13.98 12 13 12H9c-.98 0-2-1.22-2-2.5 0-.83.42-1.64 1-2.09V6.25c-1.09.53-2 1.84-2 3.25C6 11.31 7.55 13 9 13h4c1.45 0 3-1.69 3-3.5S14.5 6 13 6z"></path></svg></a>Doctype</h3>\n<p>The <a href="https://html.spec.whatwg.org/multipage/syntax.html#the-doctype">Document Type Declaration</a>\nis still required due to legacy reasons but is pragmatic compared\nto previous iterations.</p>\n<p>It\'s no longer coupled to a specific version or flavor (Strict, Traditional and\nFrameset) of an HTML specification.</p>\n<div class="gatsby-highlight">\n      <pre class="language-html"><code class="language-html"><span class="token doctype">&lt;!DOCTYPE html></span></code></pre>\n      </div>\n<h3 id="character-encoding"><a href="#character-encoding" aria-hidden="true" class="anchor"><svg aria-hidden="true" height="16" version="1.1" viewBox="0 0 16 16" width="16"><path fill-rule="evenodd" d="M4 9h1v1H4c-1.5 0-3-1.69-3-3.5S2.55 3 4 3h4c1.45 0 3 1.69 3 3.5 0 1.41-.91 2.72-2 3.25V8.59c.58-.45 1-1.27 1-2.09C10 5.22 8.98 4 8 4H4c-.98 0-2 1.22-2 2.5S3 9 4 9zm9-3h-1v1h1c1 0 2 1.22 2 2.5S13.98 12 13 12H9c-.98 0-2-1.22-2-2.5 0-.83.42-1.64 1-2.09V6.25c-1.09.53-2 1.84-2 3.25C6 11.31 7.55 13 9 13h4c1.45 0 3-1.69 3-3.5S14.5 6 13 6z"></path></svg></a>Character encoding</h3>\n<p>To target a specific character encoding for your documents to be served, you\nshould configure the <code class="language-text">Content-Type</code> header. However, we no longer need to\nprovide the <code class="language-text">http-equiv</code> and <code class="language-text">content</code> attributes.</p>\n<div class="gatsby-highlight">\n      <pre class="language-html"><code class="language-html"><span class="token tag"><span class="token tag"><span class="token punctuation">&lt;</span>meta</span> <span class="token attr-name">charset</span><span class="token attr-value"><span class="token punctuation">=</span><span class="token punctuation">"</span>UTF-8<span class="token punctuation">"</span></span><span class="token punctuation">></span></span></code></pre>\n      </div>\n<h3 id="script-references"><a href="#script-references" aria-hidden="true" class="anchor"><svg aria-hidden="true" height="16" version="1.1" viewBox="0 0 16 16" width="16"><path fill-rule="evenodd" d="M4 9h1v1H4c-1.5 0-3-1.69-3-3.5S2.55 3 4 3h4c1.45 0 3 1.69 3 3.5 0 1.41-.91 2.72-2 3.25V8.59c.58-.45 1-1.27 1-2.09C10 5.22 8.98 4 8 4H4c-.98 0-2 1.22-2 2.5S3 9 4 9zm9-3h-1v1h1c1 0 2 1.22 2 2.5S13.98 12 13 12H9c-.98 0-2-1.22-2-2.5 0-.83.42-1.64 1-2.09V6.25c-1.09.53-2 1.84-2 3.25C6 11.31 7.55 13 9 13h4c1.45 0 3-1.69 3-3.5S14.5 6 13 6z"></path></svg></a>Script references</h3>\n<p>Browsers by default assume scripts are written in JavaScript so the\n<code class="language-text">type=&quot;text/javascript&quot;</code> attribute can now be dropped.</p>\n<div class="gatsby-highlight">\n      <pre class="language-html"><code class="language-html"><span class="token tag"><span class="token tag"><span class="token punctuation">&lt;</span>script</span> <span class="token attr-name">src</span><span class="token attr-value"><span class="token punctuation">=</span><span class="token punctuation">"</span>script.js<span class="token punctuation">"</span></span><span class="token punctuation">></span></span><span class="token script language-javascript"></span><span class="token tag"><span class="token tag"><span class="token punctuation">&lt;/</span>script</span><span class="token punctuation">></span></span></code></pre>\n      </div>\n<h3 id="css-references"><a href="#css-references" aria-hidden="true" class="anchor"><svg aria-hidden="true" height="16" version="1.1" viewBox="0 0 16 16" width="16"><path fill-rule="evenodd" d="M4 9h1v1H4c-1.5 0-3-1.69-3-3.5S2.55 3 4 3h4c1.45 0 3 1.69 3 3.5 0 1.41-.91 2.72-2 3.25V8.59c.58-.45 1-1.27 1-2.09C10 5.22 8.98 4 8 4H4c-.98 0-2 1.22-2 2.5S3 9 4 9zm9-3h-1v1h1c1 0 2 1.22 2 2.5S13.98 12 13 12H9c-.98 0-2-1.22-2-2.5 0-.83.42-1.64 1-2.09V6.25c-1.09.53-2 1.84-2 3.25C6 11.31 7.55 13 9 13h4c1.45 0 3-1.69 3-3.5S14.5 6 13 6z"></path></svg></a>CSS references</h3>\n<p>We no longer need to specify <code class="language-text">type=&quot;text/css&quot;</code> when referencing external\nstylesheets.</p>\n<div class="gatsby-highlight">\n      <pre class="language-html"><code class="language-html"><span class="token tag"><span class="token tag"><span class="token punctuation">&lt;</span>link</span> <span class="token attr-name">rel</span><span class="token attr-value"><span class="token punctuation">=</span><span class="token punctuation">"</span>stylesheet<span class="token punctuation">"</span></span> <span class="token attr-name">href</span><span class="token attr-value"><span class="token punctuation">=</span><span class="token punctuation">"</span>style.css<span class="token punctuation">"</span></span><span class="token punctuation">></span></span></code></pre>\n      </div>\n<h3 id="mathml--svg"><a href="#mathml--svg" aria-hidden="true" class="anchor"><svg aria-hidden="true" height="16" version="1.1" viewBox="0 0 16 16" width="16"><path fill-rule="evenodd" d="M4 9h1v1H4c-1.5 0-3-1.69-3-3.5S2.55 3 4 3h4c1.45 0 3 1.69 3 3.5 0 1.41-.91 2.72-2 3.25V8.59c.58-.45 1-1.27 1-2.09C10 5.22 8.98 4 8 4H4c-.98 0-2 1.22-2 2.5S3 9 4 9zm9-3h-1v1h1c1 0 2 1.22 2 2.5S13.98 12 13 12H9c-.98 0-2-1.22-2-2.5 0-.83.42-1.64 1-2.09V6.25c-1.09.53-2 1.84-2 3.25C6 11.31 7.55 13 9 13h4c1.45 0 3-1.69 3-3.5S14.5 6 13 6z"></path></svg></a>MathML &#x26; SVG</h3>\n<p>These elements can now be used within an HTML document without having to specify\ntheir XML namespaces.</p>\n<h3 id="syntax"><a href="#syntax" aria-hidden="true" class="anchor"><svg aria-hidden="true" height="16" version="1.1" viewBox="0 0 16 16" width="16"><path fill-rule="evenodd" d="M4 9h1v1H4c-1.5 0-3-1.69-3-3.5S2.55 3 4 3h4c1.45 0 3 1.69 3 3.5 0 1.41-.91 2.72-2 3.25V8.59c.58-.45 1-1.27 1-2.09C10 5.22 8.98 4 8 4H4c-.98 0-2 1.22-2 2.5S3 9 4 9zm9-3h-1v1h1c1 0 2 1.22 2 2.5S13.98 12 13 12H9c-.98 0-2-1.22-2-2.5 0-.83.42-1.64 1-2.09V6.25c-1.09.53-2 1.84-2 3.25C6 11.31 7.55 13 9 13h4c1.45 0 3-1.69 3-3.5S14.5 6 13 6z"></path></svg></a>Syntax</h3>\n<p>XHTML 1.0 enforces HTML to follow the same syntax as XML: all tags in lowercase,\nattributes quoted, elements must be properly closed.</p>\n<p>HTML5 is case-insensitive and has no rules when it comes to the style of\nwriting markup.</p>\n<h3 id="content-model"><a href="#content-model" aria-hidden="true" class="anchor"><svg aria-hidden="true" height="16" version="1.1" viewBox="0 0 16 16" width="16"><path fill-rule="evenodd" d="M4 9h1v1H4c-1.5 0-3-1.69-3-3.5S2.55 3 4 3h4c1.45 0 3 1.69 3 3.5 0 1.41-.91 2.72-2 3.25V8.59c.58-.45 1-1.27 1-2.09C10 5.22 8.98 4 8 4H4c-.98 0-2 1.22-2 2.5S3 9 4 9zm9-3h-1v1h1c1 0 2 1.22 2 2.5S13.98 12 13 12H9c-.98 0-2-1.22-2-2.5 0-.83.42-1.64 1-2.09V6.25c-1.09.53-2 1.84-2 3.25C6 11.31 7.55 13 9 13h4c1.45 0 3-1.69 3-3.5S14.5 6 13 6z"></path></svg></a>Content model</h3>\n<p>This defines what child or descendant elements can be nested within an element.\nPreviously there were two major categories namely "inline" and "block-level"\nwhich had different rules based on the flavor (Strict, Traditional and Frameset)\nof HTML.</p>\n<p>These terms also caused confusion with CSS so HTML5 no longer uses them.\nInstead it categorized content based on how they can be nested.</p>\n<p>Not all elements appear in these categories but those that do can overlap\nother categories.</p>\n<ul>\n<li><strong>Metadata</strong> content e.g. <code class="language-text">link</code> &#x26; <code class="language-text">script</code></li>\n<li><strong>Flow</strong> content e.g. <code class="language-text">span</code> &#x26; <code class="language-text">div</code></li>\n<li><strong>Sectioning</strong> content e.g. <code class="language-text">aside</code> &#x26; <code class="language-text">section</code></li>\n<li><strong>Heading</strong> content e.g. <code class="language-text">h1</code> - <code class="language-text">h6</code></li>\n<li><strong>Phrasing</strong> content e.g. <code class="language-text">span</code> &#x26; <code class="language-text">img</code></li>\n<li><strong>Embedded</strong> content e.g. <code class="language-text">img</code>, <code class="language-text">iframe</code> &#x26; <code class="language-text">svg</code></li>\n<li><strong>Interactive</strong> content e.g. <code class="language-text">a</code>, <code class="language-text">button</code> &#x26; <code class="language-text">label</code></li>\n</ul>\n<h2 id="obsolete"><a href="#obsolete" aria-hidden="true" class="anchor"><svg aria-hidden="true" height="16" version="1.1" viewBox="0 0 16 16" width="16"><path fill-rule="evenodd" d="M4 9h1v1H4c-1.5 0-3-1.69-3-3.5S2.55 3 4 3h4c1.45 0 3 1.69 3 3.5 0 1.41-.91 2.72-2 3.25V8.59c.58-.45 1-1.27 1-2.09C10 5.22 8.98 4 8 4H4c-.98 0-2 1.22-2 2.5S3 9 4 9zm9-3h-1v1h1c1 0 2 1.22 2 2.5S13.98 12 13 12H9c-.98 0-2-1.22-2-2.5 0-.83.42-1.64 1-2.09V6.25c-1.09.53-2 1.84-2 3.25C6 11.31 7.55 13 9 13h4c1.45 0 3-1.69 3-3.5S14.5 6 13 6z"></path></svg></a>Obsolete</h2>\n<p>HTML5 no longer deprecates elements or attributes as it remains backwards\ncompatible instead they flag them as obsolete.</p>\n<p>They shouldn\'t be used by web developers however user agents will still have\nto support them.</p>\n<ul>\n<li>\n<p>Purely presentational</p>\n<p><code class="language-text">basefont</code>, <code class="language-text">big</code>, <code class="language-text">center</code>, <code class="language-text">font</code>, <code class="language-text">strike</code>, <code class="language-text">tt</code></p>\n</li>\n<li>\n<p>Damages usability and accessibility</p>\n<p><code class="language-text">frame</code>, <code class="language-text">frameset</code>, <code class="language-text">noframes</code></p>\n</li>\n<li>\n<p>Not used often, caused confusion or its function is handled by another element</p>\n<p><code class="language-text">acronym</code>, <code class="language-text">applet</code>, <code class="language-text">isindex</code>, <code class="language-text">dir</code></p>\n</li>\n</ul>\n<p>A number of <a href="https://www.w3.org/TR/html5-diff/#obsolete-attributes">attributes</a>\nhave also been made obsolete.</p>\n<h2 id="redefined"><a href="#redefined" aria-hidden="true" class="anchor"><svg aria-hidden="true" height="16" version="1.1" viewBox="0 0 16 16" width="16"><path fill-rule="evenodd" d="M4 9h1v1H4c-1.5 0-3-1.69-3-3.5S2.55 3 4 3h4c1.45 0 3 1.69 3 3.5 0 1.41-.91 2.72-2 3.25V8.59c.58-.45 1-1.27 1-2.09C10 5.22 8.98 4 8 4H4c-.98 0-2 1.22-2 2.5S3 9 4 9zm9-3h-1v1h1c1 0 2 1.22 2 2.5S13.98 12 13 12H9c-.98 0-2-1.22-2-2.5 0-.83.42-1.64 1-2.09V6.25c-1.09.53-2 1.84-2 3.25C6 11.31 7.55 13 9 13h4c1.45 0 3-1.69 3-3.5S14.5 6 13 6z"></path></svg></a>Redefined</h2>\n<p>Some elements have been semantically redefined.</p>\n<ul>\n<li>\n<p><code class="language-text">a</code> element now has a transparent content model. This means you are legally\nallowed to nest a <code class="language-text">div</code> element if its parent allows flow content.</p>\n</li>\n<li>\n<p><code class="language-text">b</code> element makes text stylistically bold and <strong>does not</strong> indicate importance. To\nindicate importance you should use <code class="language-text">strong</code>.</p>\n</li>\n<li>\n<p><code class="language-text">i</code> element makes text stylistically italic and <strong>does not</strong> indicate emphasis. To\nemphasize something you should use <code class="language-text">em</code>.</p>\n</li>\n<li>\n<p><code class="language-text">cite</code> element represents the title of creative work like a movie, documentary or\nbook. The browser will render the citation in italics.</p>\n</li>\n<li>\n<p><code class="language-text">small</code> element is independent of its styled presentation and is now used for\nside-comments and small print, including copyright and legal text.</p>\n</li>\n</ul>\n<h2 id="new-additions"><a href="#new-additions" aria-hidden="true" class="anchor"><svg aria-hidden="true" height="16" version="1.1" viewBox="0 0 16 16" width="16"><path fill-rule="evenodd" d="M4 9h1v1H4c-1.5 0-3-1.69-3-3.5S2.55 3 4 3h4c1.45 0 3 1.69 3 3.5 0 1.41-.91 2.72-2 3.25V8.59c.58-.45 1-1.27 1-2.09C10 5.22 8.98 4 8 4H4c-.98 0-2 1.22-2 2.5S3 9 4 9zm9-3h-1v1h1c1 0 2 1.22 2 2.5S13.98 12 13 12H9c-.98 0-2-1.22-2-2.5 0-.83.42-1.64 1-2.09V6.25c-1.09.53-2 1.84-2 3.25C6 11.31 7.55 13 9 13h4c1.45 0 3-1.69 3-3.5S14.5 6 13 6z"></path></svg></a>New additions</h2>\n<p>These elements were introduced to enhance the structure of a document:</p>\n<p><code class="language-text">section</code>, <code class="language-text">article</code>, <code class="language-text">main</code>, <code class="language-text">aside</code>, <code class="language-text">header</code>, <code class="language-text">footer</code>, <code class="language-text">nav</code>, <code class="language-text">figure</code>,\n<code class="language-text">figcaption</code>, <code class="language-text">template</code></p>\n<p>Other new elements include:</p>\n<p><code class="language-text">video</code>, <code class="language-text">audio</code>, <code class="language-text">track</code>, <code class="language-text">embed</code>, <code class="language-text">mark</code>, <code class="language-text">progress</code>, <code class="language-text">meter</code>, <code class="language-text">time</code>, <code class="language-text">ruby</code>,\n<code class="language-text">rt</code>, <code class="language-text">rp</code>, <code class="language-text">bdi</code>, <code class="language-text">wbr</code>, <code class="language-text">canvas</code>, <code class="language-text">datalist</code>, <code class="language-text">keygen</code>, <code class="language-text">output</code></p>\n<p>The <code class="language-text">input</code> element has new values for the <code class="language-text">type</code> attribute:</p>\n<p><code class="language-text">tel</code>, <code class="language-text">search</code>, <code class="language-text">url</code>, <code class="language-text">email</code>, <code class="language-text">date</code>, <code class="language-text">time</code>, <code class="language-text">number</code>, <code class="language-text">range</code>, <code class="language-text">color</code></p>\n<h2 id="javascript-apis"><a href="#javascript-apis" aria-hidden="true" class="anchor"><svg aria-hidden="true" height="16" version="1.1" viewBox="0 0 16 16" width="16"><path fill-rule="evenodd" d="M4 9h1v1H4c-1.5 0-3-1.69-3-3.5S2.55 3 4 3h4c1.45 0 3 1.69 3 3.5 0 1.41-.91 2.72-2 3.25V8.59c.58-.45 1-1.27 1-2.09C10 5.22 8.98 4 8 4H4c-.98 0-2 1.22-2 2.5S3 9 4 9zm9-3h-1v1h1c1 0 2 1.22 2 2.5S13.98 12 13 12H9c-.98 0-2-1.22-2-2.5 0-.83.42-1.64 1-2.09V6.25c-1.09.53-2 1.84-2 3.25C6 11.31 7.55 13 9 13h4c1.45 0 3-1.69 3-3.5S14.5 6 13 6z"></path></svg></a>JavaScript APIs</h2>\n<p>For a long time browser implementors were making up JavaScript APIs for\nbrowsers. Now the HTML 5 specification has sections dedicated to web application\nAPIs. Some include:</p>\n<ul>\n<li>Drag and drop</li>\n<li>Full screen</li>\n<li>History</li>\n<li>IndexDB</li>\n<li>Online and Offline events</li>\n<li>Pointer Lock</li>\n<li>Web storage</li>\n<li>Web workers</li>\n</ul>\n<hr>\n<h2 id="references"><a href="#references" aria-hidden="true" class="anchor"><svg aria-hidden="true" height="16" version="1.1" viewBox="0 0 16 16" width="16"><path fill-rule="evenodd" d="M4 9h1v1H4c-1.5 0-3-1.69-3-3.5S2.55 3 4 3h4c1.45 0 3 1.69 3 3.5 0 1.41-.91 2.72-2 3.25V8.59c.58-.45 1-1.27 1-2.09C10 5.22 8.98 4 8 4H4c-.98 0-2 1.22-2 2.5S3 9 4 9zm9-3h-1v1h1c1 0 2 1.22 2 2.5S13.98 12 13 12H9c-.98 0-2-1.22-2-2.5 0-.83.42-1.64 1-2.09V6.25c-1.09.53-2 1.84-2 3.25C6 11.31 7.55 13 9 13h4c1.45 0 3-1.69 3-3.5S14.5 6 13 6z"></path></svg></a>References</h2>\n<ul>\n<li>A Book Apart: <a href="https://abookapart.com/products/html5-for-web-designers">HTML5 for web designers</a>\nby Jeremy Keith</li>\n<li><a href="https://html.spec.whatwg.org/multipage/index.html">HTML Living Standard</a> by\nthe WHATWG (Web Hypertext Application Technology Working Group)</li>\n<li><a href="https://developer.mozilla.org/en-US/docs/Web/Guide/HTML/HTML5">HTML5 Guide</a>\nfrom Mozilla Developer Network</li>\n<li><a href="https://www.w3.org/TR/html5-diff/">Differences from HTML4</a></li>\n<li><a href="https://www.sitepoint.com/10-html5-apis-worth-looking/">10 HTML APIs worth looking into</a></li>\n</ul>',timeToRead:5,excerpt:"Elements, attributes, and attribute values are semantic according to the\nHTML5 Specification. These definitions allow HTML processors, such…",frontmatter:{title:"Design changes in HTML5",cover:"https://picsum.photos/1280/500/?image=20",date:"2016-06-16 10:00:00 +0200",category:null,tags:["Technical"]},fields:{slug:"/blog/design-changes-in-html-5"}},prev:{excerpt:"In 2005  Google sampled \nover a billion documents. This highlighted popular class names,\nelements, attributes…",frontmatter:{title:"HTML5 structural semantics",cover:"https://picsum.photos/1280/500/?image=36",date:"2016-06-17 12:02:38 +0200"},fields:{slug:"/blog/html-5-structural-semantics"}},next:{excerpt:"Improve your craft, write the cleanest code you know how at that point in time,\nlearn from your mistakes (and…",frontmatter:{title:"The horror behind design",cover:"https://picsum.photos/1280/500/?image=21",date:"2016-06-15 00:04:33 +0200"},fields:{slug:"/blog/the-horror-behind-design"}}},pathContext:{slug:"/blog/design-changes-in-html-5",total:57,prev:"/blog/html-5-structural-semantics",next:"/blog/the-horror-behind-design"}}}});
//# sourceMappingURL=path---blog-design-changes-in-html-5-df5d643af584001857cd.js.map